l function instead of inline in the class.  First of all,\nthe setuptools machinery really wants the options to be defined\nin a class attribute - otherwise, the help command doesn't work\nso we need a class attribute.  However, we are extending an\nexisting command and do not want to \"monkey patch\" over it so\nwe need to define a *new* class attribute with the same name\nthat contains a copy of the base class value.  This could be\naccomplished using some magic in `__new__` but I would much\nrather set the class attribute externally... it's just cleaner.\n"]}], "variables": [], "classes": [{"name": "mdl.third_parties.setupext_janitor.janitor.CleanCommand", "bases": ["_CleanCommand"], "methods": [{"name": "mdl.third_parties.setupext_janitor.janitor.CleanCommand.initialize_options", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": ["See _set_options for `user_options`"]}, {"name": "mdl.third_parties.setupext_janitor.janitor.CleanCommand.finalize_options", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "mdl.third_parties.setupext_janitor.janitor.CleanCommand.run", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "self", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}], "class_variables": [], "instance_variables": [], "inner_classes": [], "documentation": ["Extend the clean command to do additional house keeping.\n\nThe traditional distutils clean command removes the by-products of\ncompiling extension code.  This class extends it to remove the\nsimilar by-products generated by producing a Python distribution.\nMost notably, it will remove .egg/.egg-info directories, the\ngenerated distribution, those pesky *\\_\\_pycache\\_\\_* directories,\nand even the virtual environment that it is running in.\n\nThe level of cleanliness is controlled by command-line options as\nyou might expect.  The targets that are removed are influenced by\nthe commands that created them.  For example, if you set a custom\ndistribution directory using the `--dist-dir` option or the\nmatching snippet in *setup.cfg*, then this extension will honor\nthat setting.  It even goes as far as to detect the virtual\nenvironment directory based on environment variables.\n\nThis all sounds a little dangerous... there is little to worry\nabout though.  This command only removes what it is configured to\nremove which is nothing by default.  It also honors the\n`--dry-run` global option so that there should be no question\nwhat it is going to remove.\n", "import setupext_janitor", "backwards compat -- WILL BE REMOVED IN THE FUTURE", "version_info = setupext_janitor.version_info", "__version__ = setupext_janitor.version", "debug = False"]}], "exports": []}, {"name": "mdl.third_parties.__main__", "documentation": [], "functions": [], "variables": [{"name": "mdl.third_parties.__main__.path", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "classes": [], "exports": []}, {"name": "setup", "documentation": [], "functions": [], "variables": [{"name": "setup.here", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "setup.version", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "setup.long_description", "type": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "setup.cmd_classes", "type": null, "documentation": []}], "classes": [], "exports": []}, {"name": "mdl.third_parties", "documentation": [], "functions": [{"name": "mdl.third_parties.arg_parser", "asynchronous": false, "params": [], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "mdl.third_parties.determine_target", "asynchronous": false, "params": [], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "mdl.third_parties.download", "asynchronous": false, "params": [{"name": "**kwargs", "type": null, "default": null}], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "mdl.third_parties.integrity_check", "asynchronous": false, "params": [], "returns": null, "documentation": []}, {"name": "